    "summary": "The Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (256–125 BC) was a Hellenistic state in Central Asia (modern Afghanistan and parts of neighboring countries) that represented the farthest eastern outpost of Greek civilization, producing extraordinary coins and contributing to the cultural synthesis that later created the [[event:1104|Indo-Greek Kingdom]] and the distinctive [[event:1216|Gandhara Art]] tradition.\n\nFounded when the Seleucid satrap of Bactria, Diodotus, declared independence around 256 BC, the kingdom maintained Greek language, art, and political institutions in a region far from the Mediterranean. Its coins are considered among the finest in antiquity — large, beautifully struck with realistic royal portraits and precise inscriptions in Greek and later Kharosthi. At its height the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom controlled a territory extending from Central Asia into the Indus valley, and its rulers Demetrius I and Menander ([[event:1105|Menander I]]) pressed deep into India. The kingdom was eventually destroyed by the nomadic Yuezhi migration ([[event:1174|Yuezhi Migration]]) around 125 BC. Its cultural legacy was substantial: the Buddhist sculptural tradition of Gandhara — which produced the first human representations of the Buddha — drew directly on the Hellenistic artistic tradition left by the Greeks of Bactria.",
